Title: The Yellow Wallpaper
Credit: Screenplay adaptation of
Author: Charlotte Perkins Gilman's short story (1892, public domain)
Draft date: 7/18/2026
Notes: Tests psychological narration via V.O. against sparse scene action.

====

FADE IN:

EXT. COUNTRY ESTATE - DAY

A grand, isolated house, oddly still. A carriage arrives. JANE (20s, pale, restless) is helped down by her husband JOHN, a physician, brisk and kind in a way that brooks no argument.

JANE (V.O.)
John is practical in the extreme. He has no patience with faith, an intense horror of superstition, and he scoffs openly at any talk of things not to be felt and seen and put down in figures.

JOHN
(cheerful, firm)
The air here will do you a world of good, my dear. Rest is all you need.

JANE
(quietly)
I did not want to come.

He doesn't hear her, already walking ahead.

CUT TO:

INT. NURSERY ROOM - DAY

A large, airy room at the top of the house, barred windows, a heavy bed bolted to the floor. The walls are covered in a sprawling, sickly yellow wallpaper, its pattern chaotic and unresolved.

JANE (V.O.)
I never saw a worse paper in my life. It is dull enough to confuse the eye in following, pronounced enough to constantly irritate.

JOHN
(surveying the room, satisfied)
This will do nicely. Fresh air, quiet, and no work of any kind -- that was Weir Mitchell's whole prescription, and it will be mine as well.

JANE
(hesitant)
I think I would work better with a little companionship, John --

JOHN
(gently cutting her off)
You know the place agrees with you.

He kisses her forehead and departs. Jane looks at the wallpaper, unsettled.

CUT TO:

INT. NURSERY ROOM - DAY (LATER, ALONE)

Jane sits by the barred window, a notebook hidden beneath a blanket on her lap -- writing in secret, glancing at the door often.

JANE (V.O.)
I did write for a while in spite of them, but it does exhaust me a good deal, having to be so sly about it, or meet with heavy opposition.

Her sister-in-law, JENNIE, enters briskly to tidy the room.

JENNIE
(cheerful, oblivious)
There, now the room does look better, doesn't it?

JANE
(forcing a smile)
Much better, thank you, Jennie.

Jennie leaves. Jane's eyes drift, unwillingly, back to the wallpaper.

JANE (V.O.)
I lie here on this great immovable bed and follow that pattern about by the hour. I determine, for the thousandth time, that I will follow that pointless pattern to some sort of a conclusion.

CUT TO:

INT. NURSERY ROOM - NIGHT (WEEKS LATER)

Moonlight falls across the wallpaper. Jane sits up slowly, transfixed, tracing the pattern with her eyes.

JANE (V.O.)
By moonlight -- the moon shines in all night when there is a moon -- I wouldn't know it was the same paper.

Behind the outer pattern, faintly, something seems to shift -- a dim shape, as of a woman stooping and creeping behind the tangled bars of the design.

JANE (V.O.) (CONT'D)
(quiet, urgent)
The front pattern does move -- and no wonder! The woman behind shakes it!

CUT TO:

INT. NURSERY ROOM - DAY (LATER)

John enters to find Jane standing very close to the wall, staring fixedly.

JOHN
(concerned, gentle)
What is it, little girl?

JANE
(turning, too calm)
I'm feeling ever so much better, John. I am.

JOHN
(relieved, patting her hand)
That's my brave girl.

He leaves again for his rounds. Jane returns instantly to the wall, running her fingers along the pattern.

JANE (V.O.)
I am determined to try, little by little, to find it out. There are so many of those creeping women, and they creep so fast, that it makes me tired to follow them.

CUT TO:

INT. NURSERY ROOM - DAY (FINAL DAY)

The room is bare of furniture but the bed, bolted down as ever. Long, ragged strips of wallpaper lie torn from the walls. Jane, disheveled, creeps steadily around the perimeter of the room on hands and knees, shoulder pressed to a worn smudge along the wall.

JANE (V.O.)
I have got out at last, in spite of you and Jane. And I've pulled off most of the paper, so you can't put me back!

John's key turns in the lock. He enters, stops dead in the doorway.

JOHN
(horrified)
For God's sake, what are you doing?

JANE
(without stopping her circuit of the room, serene)
I've got out at last, in spite of you and Jane. And I've pulled off most of the paper, so you can't put me back!

John's face drains of color. He faints in the doorway.

Jane continues creeping steadily along her groove worn into the floor, stepping over him each time she passes, entirely undisturbed.

JANE (V.O.)
Now why should that man have fainted? But he did, and right across my path by the wall, so that I had to creep over him every time!

FADE OUT.

> THE END <
